Up to 25 million tonnes of wheat and other grain have been blocked in Ukrainian ports. AFP/Bulent Kilic KYIV - There is a glimmer of hope for respite from skyrocketing food prices. Turkey has brokered a deal with Russia to allow Ukraine to resume grain exports through the Black Sea. READ: India tightens flour exports after global wheat shortage The deal is expected to be signed on Friday in Turkey by Ukraine, Russia, Turkey and UN chief Antonio Guterres. It will facilitate Russian exports of grain and fertiliser via the Black Sea. READ: Tunisia struggles to grow more wheat as Ukraine war bites Both Russia and Ukraine are major exporters of wheat and cooking oil. Up to 25 million tonnes of wheat and other grain have been blocked in Ukrainian ports.